<sn><md>### Characteristics of Isobars{.text-center}

* Every point on a given isobar has the ++same atmospheric pressure++.
*  **Closed Curves**: Isobars usually form closed loops around high or low pressure centers.
* **No Crossing**: Isobars never intersect each other since a location cannot have two different pressures at the same time.
* **Relation with Wind**: Wind generally flows nearly ++parallel to isobars++ due to the Coriolis force, but slightly across them toward low pressure due to friction.
</md></sn><sn><md>### Isobars and Pressure Gradient Force{.text-center}

The **pressure gradient force (PGF)** arises due to differences in pressure across horizontal distances.

+++ view diagram
![diagram](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Nh-emon/QDoc/main/SES%202nd%20Year/Atmospheric%20Chemistry/media/svg/isobar-distance-diagram.svg)
+++

* If two isobars are **close together**, the PGF is stronger, leading to high wind speeds.
* If two isobars are **far apart**, the PGF is weaker, producing gentle winds.

Mathematically, the PGF is expressed as:

$$
PGF = -\frac{1}{\rho} \frac{\Delta P}{\Delta n}
$$



+++ Where:

* $\rho$ = air density
* $\Delta P$ = pressure difference
* $\Delta n$ = distance between isobars
+++
</md></sn><sn><md>### Types of Isobaric Patterns{.text-center}

:::.row

:::.col-12 .col-lg-7
1. **High Pressure (Anticyclone)**: Isobars form roughly circular, `outward-spreading loops`. Winds move outward and clockwise in the Northern Hemisphere.
2. **Low Pressure (Cyclone)**: Isobars form `inward-closing loops`. Winds move inward and counterclockwise in the Northern Hemisphere.
3. **Troughs and Ridges**: Elongated low-pressure and high-pressure zones represented by curved isobar lines.
